    value: 순(舜) 임금의 눈에 동자가 둘씩 있었다 한다. 그러므로 임금의 눈을 중동이라 한 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 정호(鼎胡)의 궁검(弓劍) : '
    value: 황제(黃帝)가 정호에서 신선이 되어 용을 타고 하늘로 올라갈 때에 활과 칼을 떨어뜨렸다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 조아(爪牙) : '
    value: 맹수(猛獸)가 어금니와 발톱[爪牙]으로 몸을 보호하므로 무장(武將)을 임금의 어금니와 발톱이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 우물 물이 …… 되자 : '
    value: 신라 말기에 이런 재변이 있었다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 겁화(劫火) : '
    value: 불경에, “천지가 없어질 때에 불이 일어나 모든 것을 태우는 것을 겁화(劫火)라 한다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 용상(龍象) : '
    value: 인도(印度)에서는 동물 중에 용과 코끼리를 으뜸으로 여기므로 높은 중들을 용상(龍象)이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 春 : '
    value: 舂
english:
  title: Eight Views of Gyerim with Preface
  author: Cho Wei
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When Su Dongpo served as prefect of Fengxiang, he composed verses on ancient sites and called them the Eight Views. Among them were the Vimalakirti Portrait painted by Wang Wei and Wu Daozi, and the tower of Zhenxing Temple—things seen at a single Buddhist monastery that need not have been written about at all. Gyerim, the ancient capital of Silla, once flourished with magnificent culture and refinement, yet today all has faded into obscurity. Still, its ruins remain countable and distinct. I, bearing the commission of the provincial inspector, passed through this place en route to my post. First I paid respects at the shrine of our Great Ancestor, then wandered through the old sites of Silla, my heart stirred with emotion. Some of what moved me found voice in verse, and these too I have called the Eight Views—not that I presume to emulate the great Dongpo, but simply because eight poems emerged. Among them are Lingmiao Temple and the Golden Repository Platform. Though they lack momentous deeds to record, Lingmiao was founded during the Zhenguan era of Tang and stands solitary and majestic to this day, while the Golden Repository overlooks all of Gyerim without obstruction—the very pinnacle of the city's beauty. Thus I have rendered both in regulated verse, that future visitors might enjoy them. Alas, Gyerim lies remote on the eastern sea, ten thousand li from the Middle Kingdom. Had the venerable Dongpo but once come and beheld these sights, his magnificent prose would have thundered through the three kingdoms of Korea. Would his compositions have stopped at merely eight views? Is this not the misfortune of this land?

    *On the Hall of Gathered Celebration*

    The treasure hall stands solemn in dimming shadow,
    Dawn light ascends in radiant splendor.
    On the Jade Pool, colored banners array,
    Around embroidered halls, fragrant incense swirls.
    Palace officials open the great gates,
    And green locks deepen in the gathering dusk.
    A humble servant bows to touch his head,
    Reverently gazing upon the celestial countenance.

    That dragon-visage and solar-marked brow—
    Such brilliance is rare in all the world.
    How could such luminous gaze,
    Born from the wonder of brushwork,
    Not humble me with trembling awe?
    Sweat drenches through my robe.

    Alas, I was born too late,
    The tripod and sword of old are distant dreams.
    Yet vast and boundless is his virtue—
    Great Founder, Pacifier of the People,
    Your merit matches Heaven itself.

    When Goryeo's fortune waned and fell,
    Confusion reigned with ceaseless strife.
    You, through years of arduous campaign,
    South and north subduing as Heaven ordained,
    With godlike strategies and swift-sweeping might,
    Transformed the people's groans to peaceful song.

    The six dragons soared into the sky,
    The solar chariot claimed its proper course.
    You opened the capital on Hwa Mountain's southern slope,
    Making it splendid as Fenghao of old.

    Great works of peace were instituted,
    Culture and refinement reached their height.
    The patterns of former ages now seem crude,
    Yet the legacy you left shows no haste.
    Your enlightened descendants continue without end—
    Your image guards this ancient city still,
    Your sacred spirit dwells in Heaven's vault.

    *On the Tomb of King Muryeol*

    In the fields beside a country road,
    Green wheat has shot up tall.
    A lone peak rises, just a few spans high,
    Like some great beast in slumber crouched.
    A broken stele lies beneath the grass,
    Its turtle-head raised defiant still.
    Wild and desolate spreads the moorland,
    Where waters wind through distant vales.

    This, men say, is Muryeol's resting place—
    A royal tomb built with the mountain's form,
    No pretense of grandeur or display.
    I dismount; my hair stands on end.
    Standing still with reverence, sleeves drawn close,
    I trace the weathered characters of stone,
    But erosion renders them illegible.

    The ages stretch before me, empty and vast,
    Left unguarded, crumbling into neglect.
    I think of days when darkness became light,
    When imposters sat where true queens should reign,
    When fierce neighbors pressed their invasions,
    And the four borders burned with endless war.

    Then came the King to claim the mandate true,
    His merit shone resplendent and supreme.
    To faithful generals he entrusted command—
    His martial wisdom seemed Heaven-sent.
    He united North and South, opening an age of dominion,
    Swept away a century of plunder and strife.

    Tang's ruler recognized his great deeds,
    Bestowing gifts of silk and treasure untold.
    And all men of talent flocked to serve,
    While granaries swelled with daily abundance.

    Yet sudden calamity—the well ran red with blood,
    And the great fortune could not be preserved.
    The sword and sash passed to the underworld,
    His brilliant spirit ascended to the stars.

    Old records offer fragmentary testimony,
    Yet their accounts remain incomplete.
    Human affairs are but passing clouds—
    Who can fathom the cosmos entire?

    His fairest city lies forever still,
    As evening falls and field mice cry.

    *On Lingmiao Temple*

    The ancient temple fronts upon the great road,
    Its towers soar to heaven's height.
    Roof beams stand lower than the passing clouds,
    While ridge-ends catch the rising sea-sun.
    Sleeping mist clings to the golden plaques,
    Andflowing twilight hides the crimson boards.

    Elaborate galleries open beyond the sky,
    Wind-chimes echo through the emptiness above.
    Brilliant Buddha-forms in majesty stand,
    Their colored auras gleaming bright.
    On every wall the blue and scarlet dance,
    With countless figures of devas and men.

    Bejeweled canopies and treasure-crowned umbrellas
    Swirl and gather in confused splendor.
    I gaze within a moment at these wonders—
    Such magnitude confounds the eye.

    This could not be the work of mortal hands alone—
    My heart stirrs with awe and ancient memory.

    Queen Sondok once presided over dawn,
    And raised the Buddha's teaching far too high.
    A single timber cost a hundred pieces of gold,
    Each foundation stone a million coins consumed.

    Through years of building, treasuries were emptied,
    Yet did the people not resent such waste?
    The hoped-for blessings never came to pass—
    The merits all vanished into futility.

    Though thousand years of cosmic fire have passed,
    This temple stands, protecting the highest monks.
    The palace and markets of that age lie bare,
    Yet still we marvel at this ghostly feat.

    Counting back the years of Zhenguan's reign—
    I clap my hands before the wind.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Heavy-browed eyes with double pupils were said to mark the legendary sage-king Shun, and by extension, any ruler with extraordinary virtue and perception.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to the tripod and sword relates to the Yellow Emperor's legendary ascension to heaven at Dinghu, where he supposedly dropped these items as he departed.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'blood in the well' was considered an omen of national disaster in the Silla period.
  - key: ''
    value: The Zhenguan era refers to the prosperous reign of Tang Taizong (627-649 CE), used here as a marker of temporal distance.
